(684, 2, '<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img11.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-696" alt="img1" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/img11-1024x568.jpg" width="625" height="346" /></a>The idea of 3D printer has been extended to the food industry to make 3D objects, which are edible to eat. Two 3D printers will be launched this year, ChefJet and ChefJetPro by the American manufacturer, 3D Systems. These new 3D food printers are able to print edible objects made up of milk chocolate or sugar and are available in 4 flavours, viz. mint, sour apple, watermelon and cherry flavours. 3D Systems’ Liz von Hasseln explains that, a very fine layer of sugar is spread and then water is painted on the surface of the sugar so that the sugar can recrystallize and take the shape of any geometric object, they design. The designing is done using a computer-aided design (CAD) program. The users can select the design from the existing ones, or create a new design of their own and send the design to the printer to generate new, colourful and edible 3D objects. Liz Von Hasseln and her husband Kyle had opened a Sugar Lab in September 2013, a company where people could order 3D printed sugary creations. Later, 3D Systems contacted them with an offer to buy the company and turn their modified Cube printers into their own line: the ChefJet and the ChefJetPro.\r\n\r\nThe prices of ChefJet and ChefJetPro will be around $5000 and $10,000 respectively (exact prices are yet to be announced). The former one produces single-colour edible prints for items like sugar cubes and cake decorations. It can print objects of 8 x 8 x 6 inches. ChefJetPro can print multi-coloured objects or ceramics of the dimensions 10 x 14 x 8 inches.\r\n\r\nAlso the availability of a “Digital Cookbook” will allow the users to choose the designs and print 3D edible objects easily. The ChefJet and ChefJetPro are the first professionally certified, kitchen-ready 3D food printers, on display at 3D System''s stand at CES this week. Both will be available in the second half of 2014.', '3D Food Printer: Creates Sweets and Chocolates', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=684'),
(700, 5, '[caption id="attachment_703" align="aligncenter" width="605"]<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Lenovo_IdeaPad_A10_Black_BIG.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-703  " alt="Lenovo-Ideapad-A10" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Lenovo_IdeaPad_A10_Black_BIG.jpg" width="605" height="615" /></a> Lenovo-Ideapad-A10[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe launch of the first <strong>Lenovo Android-based dual-mode notebook</strong> is announced. The 10-point multi-touch notebook is capable of flipping 300 degrees. It weighs around 1 kilograms and has a 10.1-inch (1366 x 768 pixels) display. The processor is a 1.6GHz quad-core ARM Cortex A9 processor and the battery life is said to be of 10 hours. It also offers 16GB of internal memory, integrated graphics supported by 2GB of RAM, along with integrated speakers and a webcam of 0.3M. It supports 2 modes: Laptop and Stand and is priced at <strong>Rs. 19,990</strong>.\r\n\r\nThe specifications include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>10.1-inch (1366 x 768 pixels) 10-point multi-touch display</li>\r\n	<li>1.6GHz quad-core ARM Cortex A9 processor</li>\r\n	<li>Lenovo customized Android 4.2 OS</li>\r\n	<li>Dimensions: 269 mm x 185 mm x 17.3 mm; Weight: 1 kg (approx.)</li>\r\n	<li>0.3MP front-facing camera</li>\r\n	<li>1 GB DDR3 RAM, 16 GB internal memory</li>\r\n	<li>1 Micro USB, 2 USB 2.0, Micro HDMI, TF, (Micro SD) card reader, Audio Combo Jack, (headphone and mic)</li>\r\n	<li>Integrated speakers</li>\r\n	<li>AccuType keyboard</li>\r\n	<li>2 cell 22.6WH battery that offers upto 9 hours video playback and up to 39 hours audio playback</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Lenovo launches Ideapad A10 in India', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=700'),
(706, 2, '[caption id="attachment_707" align="aligncenter" width="512"]<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Smart-Contact-Lens-1.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-707 " alt="Smart Contact Lens" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Smart-Contact-Lens-1.jpg" width="512" height="371" /></a> Smart Contact Lens by Google[/caption]\r\n<blockquote>Google has introduced a new <em><strong>‘Smart Contact Lens’</strong></em> that is capable of measuring the glucose level in the blood from the tears. This invention can be proved as a boon to the people suffering from Diabetes. Diabetic patients will then be free from the finger pricking method to test the amount of glucose in the blood every now and then. These lens use a tiny wireless chip and a miniaturised glucose sensor which is embedded between the two layers of the lens material.\r\n\r\nGoogle says that the chip and sensors on the lens are so small that they appear to be <em>''bits of glitter''</em> and are thinner than a <em>''human hair''</em>. Embedded between two soft layers of the lens, these sensors will be able to monitor the glucose level. Also, they are exploring ways to embed<em> <strong>thin tiny LED lights</strong></em> inside the lens that will glow when the glucose level increases or decreases a particular value, to warn the user regarding the glucose level. <em><strong>Brian Otis</strong></em> and <em><strong>Babak Parviz</strong></em> are the co-founders of this project. Google has developed the prototypes of these lens for testing purposes and has already done many clinical tests on it. Google said that it was testing a prototype of the lens that could "generate a reading once per second". Though the approvals from the <em><strong>FDA (Food and Drug Administration)</strong></em> are pending, Google is looking for potential partners to launch this product in the market.</blockquote>', 'Google’s new ‘Smart Contact Lens’ measures Glucose levels for Diabetics', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=706'),
(715, 5, '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Have you ever feared if some of your important messages or anything you do with your phone become  public to all which you don''t want?</strong></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Geeksphone-Blackphone.jpg">\r\n<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-719" alt="Blackphone" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Geeksphone-Blackphone.jpg" width="230" height="219" hspace="10px" vspace="10px" /></a></p>\r\nThen here is a phone that can claims to give you best privacy in the world even from NSA it''s <strong>Blackphone</strong> from <strong>Geeksphone</strong> .\r\n\r\nGeeksphone, a company that has been known for their work with the Firefox OS has just announced the development of the Blackphone. While details about the hardware are scant, the company has said that it would be an Android based phone running a top of the line processor with focus purely on privacy and security. The company has said that the phone would not offer stock Android, but instead would be running a “PrivatOS” interface that  would allow users to make and receive private phonecalls and messages.\r\n\r\nWeb browsing would be made private through means of a built in Anonymous VPS service courtesy Silent Circle,a company that happens to be a key partner in the Blackphone project.\r\n\r\nGeeksphone has said that the phone will be showcased at MWC  (Mobile World Congress)  next month and pre-orders should begin by the end of February. Currently, there is no word on actual specifications of the phone or the price, but what we do know for sure is that the phone will be offered as an unlocked device, meaning it can be bought and used on any GSM carrier.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/blackphone.jpg">\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-718" alt="Blackphone" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/blackphone.jpg" width="600" height="334" /></a>\r\n\r\nHowever, the Blackphone will create one major concern; security. A phone with a completely private and encrypted network, incapable of being monitored or hacked would be a terrorist’s dream phone. What is to keep unsavory elements from using the Blackphone for actions that endanger national or global security?\r\n\r\nYou can watch this video by the people who are the brains behind this project to get more insight into what sparked the creation of the Blackphone.\r\n\r\n<center><iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/BKUb7LGdvhE" height="315" width="560" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="5"></iframe></center>', 'Meet the World''s most secured phone ', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=715'),
(738, 5, '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-743" alt="post2" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.jpg" width="600" height="391" /></a>Virtual reality has captured the imagination of developers, consumers and businesses for decades, but most VR headsets produced so far have been notable more for their limitations than their capabilities. With its latest prototype, code-named "Crystal Cove," Oculus VR has taken a massive leap forward, eliminating the stomach-churning motion blur that has plagued previous generations of VR headsets, and adding sensors and a camera to track the position of both your head and body and provide more accurate simulated movement. With the latest Rift, Oculus has created a device that may usher in an era of truly immersive gaming and entertainment, and even create new opportunities for businesses to use virtual reality in everything from manufacturing to medical environments. Of all the exciting, innovative products we''ve seen at CES this year, the Oculus Rift "Crystal Cove" prototype is unquestionably the best of the best.</p>\r\n<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post1.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-742" alt="oculus rift" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post1.jpg" width="540" height="360" /></a>The Crystal Cove version''s 1080p OLED display is amazingly sharp and bright. However, what really sets it apart is its positional-tracking capabilities, accomplished thanks to an array of sensors mounted around the edges of the unit, which are monitored by an external camera. It''s no longer just your head that controls movement; lean forward or back, and the virtual environment moves in sync, providing an unparalleled, fully immersive experience. Use the new Rift for a few minutes, and you may never want to take it off; at the very least, it may change the way you think about gaming, and make that 55-inch TV hooked up to your console feel small and constricting\r\n\r\nThe Rift has broad applications beyond gaming, and Oculus VP Nate Mitchell tells us that the company has sold developer kits to companies in virtually every industry, from auto manufacturers to the movie business (and, yes, Mitchell admits that there are military applications for the technology). NASA is already using the Rift to create virtual tours of Mars and the International Space Station, and Mitchell points out that the Rift is getting a lot of interest from the training and educational communities. Virtual reality, says Mitchell, is a "new disruptive medium that can revolutionize the way we do a lot more than just games." Forbes is already referring to the way businesses are looking to capitalize on VR as the "Oculus Rift effect."<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post3.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-744" alt="post3" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post3.jpg" width="460" height="287" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The biggest challenge for Oculus is getting the Rift in the hands of consumers, and the company remains quiet about a release date, with Mitchell saying only that "2014 is going to be a big year for VR." It already is, now that Oculus has started the year as the winner of the official Best of CES Award for 2014.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">At the moment, Oculus Rift is only available in a $300 kit aimed at game developers. But once you strap on this virtual-reality headset onto your noggin and experience it in action, you’ll get itchy for the consumer release, which is scheduled for 2014. Used with a PC or Android device, Rift will let games create 3D worlds which surround you — you can even look over your shoulder for enemies lurking behind. If the games live up to the hardware’s potential, it could be an epoch-shifting landmark.</p>', 'Oculus rift - Virtual reality taken to the NeXt LeVeL', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=738'),
(740, 1, 'Intex mobiles as been promised to release its Octa Core Smartphone has released it and was seen at <a href="http://www.snapdeal.com/product/intex-aqua-octa-black/1132643279">Snapdeal</a>.Its priced at Rs.19999 just under the 20,000Rs mark which almost makes it a budget octa core smartphones.This anticipated phone was reviewed a month ago by <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zr1qAST2Zw4" target="_blank">Technixmedia</a> where we get the first look of this octa core phone.This is a phablet having 6-inch hefty screen with 1280 X 720 pixels HD IPS display which is based on One-Glass-Solution(OGS).It is powered by a 1.7GHz true Octa-Core which means that there are no 2-quad core chipsets.It has a Mali-450 MP4 GPU and runs on Android 4.2 Jellybean.It packs a 13-megapixel auto focus rear camera with LED Flash and a 5-megapixel front-facing camera similar to the Aqua i7. It comes with Dual SIM support with dual standby.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Intex-Aqua-Octa.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-747" alt="Intex-Aqua-Octa" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Intex-Aqua-Octa.jpg" width="560" height="692" /></a>\r\n\r\nIntex has officialy launched it and Commenting on the launch, Sanjay Kumar Kalirona, Business Head – Mobile, Intex Technologies Ltd. said,\r\n<blockquote>The launch of ‘Aqua Octa’ reinforces our brand’s promise to bring premium smart devices at the leading edge of technology, to improve the quality of life of people at large. With the True Octa Core processor, Intex achieves another industry first by bringing the fastest 6-inch Android smartphone ever for the technically savvy customer. The incredibly responsive touch screen and innovative user interface adds that ‘plus one’ that our customers have come to expect from every Intex device.</blockquote>\r\n<strong>Intex Aqua Octa specifications</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>6-inch (1280 x 720 pixels) HD IPS OGS display</li>\r\n	<li>1.7 GHz Octa-core MediaTek MT6592 processor with 700 MHz Mali 450-MP4 GPU</li>\r\n	<li>Android 4.2 (Jelly Bean)</li>\r\n	<li>Dual SIM (WCDMA+GSM)</li>\r\n	<li>13MP auto focus camera with LED Flash, 1080p Full HD video recording</li>\r\n	<li>5MP front-facing camera</li>\r\n	<li>3.5mm audio jack, FM Radio, dual Yamaha 1420 speakers with 1.2W output</li>\r\n	<li>Dimensions - 161.06×80.86x7mm; Weight: 180 grams</li>\r\n	<li>3G HSPA+, Wi-Fi 802.11 b/g/n, Bluetooth, aGPS</li>\r\n	<li>2GB RAM, 16GB internal memory</li>\r\n	<li>2300 mAh battery with up to 6 hours talk time and up to 180 hours standby</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt will be available in all stores from Jan 15th onwards and also in e-commerce websites which has also been listed in snapdeal already.', 'Intex Aqua Octa India''s First OctaCore Phone ', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=740'),
(754, 5, '<div><a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.1.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-753" alt="post2.1" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.1.jpg" width="189" height="189" /></a> Good news for hacker as they can listen and record private conversations even after you close a tab in Google Chrome.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>A new bug in Google Chrome, allows malicious sites to get control of  your microphone, and listen in on anything said around your computer, even after you’ve closed those tabs</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div> This bug works even if you are not using your computer, but take any phone calls and conversations around your laptop. Some malicious sites can, literally convert your Google chrome into a call tapper, and record and compromise conversations in your home or office as long as Chrome is running.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>The root of this problem is Chrome''s microphone permissions policy. Once the user has given an HTTPS-enabled site permission to use your microphone in Chrome, every feature on the site has complete permission. Chrome does not give any visual indication that Speech Recognition is turned on which allows it to run undetected. The only known  solution to the problem is, if the user manually removes the microphone permission!!</div>\r\n<div>The bug was first reported in September,2013 by developer Tal Ater and was nominated for Chromium’s Reward Panel. Although Google''s engineer''s were able to isolate the problem,  the solution couldn''t reach the desktop users even after 4 months.</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.3.jpg"><img class="wp-image-756 alignleft" alt="post2.3" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/post2.3.jpg" width="423" height="212" /></a>With Google, Apple and other internet giants working on improving voice search, this could pose as a serious problem. And as apps become more common, the privacy problem would only grow with them. Ater says that''s what makes the bug so serious. "Authorizing a site to use speech recognition will soon be as common as talking to Siri," he said.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>A Google spokesperson said, "we’ve re-investigated and still believe there is no immediate threat, since a user must first enable speech recognition for each site that requests it. The feature is in compliance with the current W3C standard, and we continue to work on improvements."</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div></div>', 'Is Google Chrome - A distant kin of the NSA??', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=754'),
(772, 1, 'After Intex been launched its flagship and India''s own first Octa-Core Phone  the <a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/smartphones/intex-aqua-octa-indias-first-octacore-phone/">Intex Aqua Octa</a> , Micromax is also not so far behind.It has launched its flagship smartphone Micromax Canvas Knight A350 its own Octa-Core smartphone.The device is launched in Russia currently as of 25 Jan 2014 and expected to launch in India soon.Just few days back Micromax A200 got listed in the website.\n\nMicromax Official Russia Website : <a href="http://www.micromaxinfo.com/ru/">www.micromaxinfo.com/ru/</a>\n\nYou may also see : <a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/android-phone/micromax-a200-specs-leaked-on-mmxnewscaster/">http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/android-phone/micromax-a200-specs-leaked-on-mmxnewscaster/</a>\n\nThe smartphone has got a 5 inch full HD 1080p IPS display and is 7.3mm thick.It is clocked at 2 Ghz Octa Core processor with 2 GB of RAM.Internal memory is of 32 GB and cannot be extended due to absence of MicroSD card slot.The phone has a MicroSIM slot.The phone as was expected to run on Kitkat but unfortunately runs on Jelly Bean 4.2.And also we assume the phone will get the Kikat update later.But the battery comes with a 2350mAh spec and is slightly disappointing as 3000 mAh would have been given more battery life for an Octa Core phone.Still officially the standby time and the talktime is not disclosed yet.It comes with a 16MP Rear and 5MP front camera which makes it to make two ways HD recording.The phone has a single LED flash.This phone almost resembles the iPhone in terms of the design.Take a look at the pic carefully.\n\n<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Micromax-Canvas-knight-A350.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-large wp-image-774" alt="Micromax-Canvas-knight-A350" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/Micromax-Canvas-knight-A350-935x1024.jpg" width="625" height="684" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/1901592_676580802405226_541097980_n.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1077" alt="1901592_676580802405226_541097980_n" src="http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/1901592_676580802405226_541097980_n.jpg" width="873" height="960" /></a>Key Specs:\n<ul>\n	<li>5 inch IPS display with Full HD resolution.</li>\n	<li>Android 4.2 Jelly Bean OS.</li>\n	<li>2.0GHz octa core processor.</li>\n	<li>2GB RAM.</li>\n	<li>16MP Rear camera; 5MP Front.</li>\n	<li>Single LED Flash.</li>\n	<li>Colors Availability:  White and Black.</li>\n	<li>Dual SIM.</li>\n	<li>32GB Internal Memory.</li>\n	<li>2350mAh Battery.</li>\n</ul>\nCurrently there are no other details or information on the price tag for this flagship smartphone, but is expected to arrive in India with a price range of 20000-25000Rs.\n\n&nbsp;\nImage originally published at <a href="http://images.maxabout.com/misc/infographics/image/micromax-canvas-knight-a350-specifications-and-expected-price"></a>Maxabout', 'Micromax Canvas Knight A350 First Octa Core Smartphone', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=772'),
(780, 2, '<h4><i><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Time Complexity:</span></i></h4>\r\n<blockquote>The very next word that we often hear with ''<b>Algorithms</b>'' is <b>''Time Complexity''</b>. So what is time complexity? It is the <b>time taken</b> for an algorithm to compute its output, expressed as a function of the length of the user''s input. In simple words, it is a concept, determining how much time an algorithm will take for its completion. Time complexity can also be termed as the <b>number of elementary row operations</b> that are performed in a given algorithm; where the time taken by an elementary row operation <b>may differ</b> from machine to machine. This concept of time complexity is mainly useful, when the size of input by the user is <b>infinitely large</b>. Usually described in <b>big O notation</b>, time complexity is sometimes also described in terms of big theta notation, small O notation, etc.</blockquote>\r\n<h4><i><span style="text-decoration: underline;">The need to study time complexity:</span></i></h4>\r\n<blockquote>To handle the real time problems and scenarios, we need to develop applications that can be used to either solve, or atleast simplify the problem such that it can be solved. All applications are based on algorithms. The <b>accuracy</b> of the algorithms, is what determines whether that application will be accepted by the users or not. The time taken by that algorithm to compute the output is important. And hence, we need to learn and calculate the <b>''time complexity''</b> of that algorithm. The immediate question arising now will be, that the machines and the processors that the users use, are different. The time taken to compute the output for a particular machine, need not be the same as that taken by some other machine running a different processor. Then how are we supposed to calculate the <b>dependency of the algorithm</b>? This creates an urge to calculate the time complexity of an algorithm, <b>independent of the type of the machine</b> and the processor.</blockquote>\r\n<h4><i><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Time Complexity Calculation:</span></i></h4>\r\n<blockquote>Assuming that a machine takes 1 unit of time to execute one elementary operation, let us calculate the time taken by the machine to run a loop. The following example explains the time complexity calculation for a <b>for loop</b>.\r\n\r\n<code> <i>for (int i=1; i&lt;=10; i++)\r\nprint Hello.\r\nprint ''Out of loop''.</i></code>\r\n\r\nLet us first see how this for loop works. The system first executes the initiation statement (int i=1) once. This assigns the value 1 to the variable i. Then the value of i (=1) will be checked by the condition statement (i&lt;=10). If satisfied, the contents of the loop are executed, followed by the execution of the incrementing statement (i++). While the loop is functioning, the variable i will be incremented for 10 times, right from i=2 to i=11, where it will come out of the loop, because i=11 does not satisfy the condition statement of the loop. The condition statement will be executed for 11 times, right from checking when i=1 (after the execution of the initiation statement) to i=11 where it''ll return false. Also, the contents of the loop are executed 10 times. So in general, if we try to calculate the time complexity of the <b>for loop</b>:\r\n\r\n<code> <i>for (int i=1; i&lt;=n; i++)\r\nprint Hello.\r\nprint ''Out of loop''.</i></code>\r\n\r\nwe can say that the total number of time units, that the machine will take to execute this loop will be the sum of:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Initiation statement: 1</li>\r\n	<li>Condition statement: (n+1)</li>\r\n	<li>Incrementing statement: n</li>\r\n	<li>Contents of the loop: n*(1) since there is only one print statement in the loop.</li>\r\n	<li>The last statement: 1</li>\r\n	<li><b>Total: 3n+3</b></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHence, the time complexity of this algorithm can be given as <strong>O(n)</strong>. We ignore the other constants here. This is because, we are only interested in calculating the time taken by the algorithm, when the user''s input is infinitely large. When n approaches infinity, the constant ''3'' holds <em><strong>no significant value</strong></em> as compared to infinity. We are interested in, how the time taken, varies with n; which is <em><strong>linearly</strong></em> in this case. This type of calculation helps us to compare the algorithms to be used in the real time problems, because, we want the output to be delivered as fast as possible, and realizing that the algorithm is slower, after the implementation of that algorithm has been done, doesn''t make us any <em><strong>good engineers</strong></em>.\r\n\r\n<b>Coming Soon:</b> <a href="#">Big O, small θ, small O notations in Time Complexity</a>\r\n<b>Keep following to be updated!!</b></blockquote>', 'Time Complexity Simplified', 'http://www.itechnospot.com/blog/?p=780');
